##Chinese Preventive Medicine Association Expert Group: "The inflection point is not the darkness before dawn, only equivalent to 12 o'clock at night"

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

"Disease Control, like fire control, has the power of decision and disposal in the handling of an epidemic. "

Starting on the sixth day of the Lunar New Year (January 30) , Li Liming, the first director of the CDC and a professor at the public health, led a group of domestic public health cadres to work together. He led a team called the "Chinese Association of Preventive Medicine Covid-19 Pneumonia Prevention expert group, " the work mainly includes the evaluation of the entire epidemic prevention and control operation, to provide support for prevention and control technology, and Monitor public opinion.

On February 16, the key members of the Expert Group were interviewed by China News weekly during the critical period of the prevention and control of NCP. Besides Li Liming, the experts also include: Wang Hua, president of the Society of Preventive Medicine of Jiangsu Province, former director of Jiangsu Provincial Center for Disease Control and Prevention, and deputy director of the Provincial Health Department; Fudan University, former director of the public health, Professor of epidemiology, former consultant to the health bureau of the Macau Government, Tang Jinling, director of clinical research and emeritus professor of epidemiology at the Chinese University of Hong Kong, Guangzhou Women and Children Medical Center; Hao Yuantao, dean of the Public Health at National Sun Yat-sen University and professor of the Department of Medical Statistics and Epidemiology; Fung Permadi, Dean of the Nanjing Medical University and professor of the biostatistics at public health; Ren Jun, former director of the Anhui CDC, and others.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 16, Li Liming, the first director of the CDC, led an expert group on the prevention and control of pneumonia from the COVID-19 in an interview with China News Weekly in Beijing.

"This monitoring system is not responsible for Emerging Infectious Diseases. " 

China News Weekly: China's Disease Control System established a direct reporting system to monitor infectious diseases after SARS, but this line of defense didn't seem to work in time for the early stages of the epidemic, what part of the monitoring might have gone wrong?

Wang Hua: Before SARS, our country began to set up a sensitive epidemic reporting system, which can be linked up and down in the whole country. After SARS, the construction of this system was accelerated. This system is integrated by the medical institutions and health institutions, Class A, B infectious diseases, confirmed in the online reporting directly, Class C infectious diseases surveillance only report.

According to the law on the prevention and control of infectious diseases, only the National Health Administration and its delegated provincial health administration have the right to make public the epidemic situation, the National Center for Disease Control and Prevention and local centers for Disease Control and Prevention do not have any power to publicize the epidemic.

In addition, an important issue is that the Emerging Infectious Diseases is not covered by the report, which means that the monitoring system is not responsible for finding Emerging Infectious Diseases.

China Newsweek: So how does the Emerging Infectious Diseases Monitor and report?

Wang Hua: There is another reporting system for suspected public health emergencies. The system sets the number, scope and timing of the reports. It is a suspected case and therefore is not made public. It is subject to Expert Assessment, Verification and diagnosis to determine if it constitutes a public health emergency, it's a time-consuming process. So this has exposed us in the system and the standard design existence question.

Li Liming: In the law on the prevention and control of infectious diseases, there is only one sentence for these Emerging Infectious Diseases, that is to say, to report, but there are no clear rules on how to report. So in January 20 or so, the state new coronavirus pneumonia as a "B infectious disease, according to the management of a" , since every day began to report. Before this, there is no qualitative what it is, how harmful, there is a need for expert evaluation and Health Administration decision-making process.

Jiang Qingwu: The world may also find it difficult to find such a strong direct epidemic reporting system in China, which has played a great role in the management of known infectious diseases, and its disadvantage is that it does not cover the Emerging Infectious Diseases.

My advice on how to improve it is to strengthen "symptom surveillance" rather than "disease surveillance" for a Emerging Infectious Diseases. Because in the beginning, when a new disease appears, no one knows what it is, but often its manifestations are nothing more than fever, cough, diarrhea, vomiting, muscle soreness, and so on. These are all very sensitive evidence, we need to test for these symptoms.

Li Liming: This new outbreak is coming at the right time for our flu, pneumonia, or what used to be called Atypical pneumonia, which is also the season for a lot of respiratory infections. Therefore, in the short term to detect a respiratory infectious disease is a new disease, or a certain amount of time and testing to determine. We recently prepared a proposal to the government to have a specialized, sensitive surveillance system for respiratory infections, and to report all relevant symptoms, and then sift through them to see what's Emerging Infectious Diseases and what's already there.

Wang Hua: At present, the fever clinic, the surveillance system of pneumonia of unknown cause and the influenza surveillance system are all scattered in the management of medical institutions. In the course of consultation, the discovery of unexplained pneumonia patients, according to the request should be reported immediately, but in practice no one care. Clinicians are busy, and reporting it means a lot of paperwork and investigation to do, which is an extra burden for them. So experts have long argued for a mechanism for diagnosis, reporting, treatment and containment. Specifically, for example, could an improvement be made to the hospital's electronic diagnosis and treatment system, so that when a doctor sees a patient with pneumonia of unknown origin, he doesn't have to fill out another form, he just clicks a button in his system, this case can be sent to the surveillance system.

"first thing you need is a epidemiologist. " 

China Newsweek: In the early days of the epidemic, the criteria for the diagnosis of NCP included a history of exposure to the south China seafood market and fever, but not every patient could meet these conditions at the same time. This created a problem, the hospital admitted a lot of suspected patients, but because does not meet the conditions for diagnosis, can not report. What does that tell you?

Li Liming: one of the major characteristics of Emerging Infectious Diseases is that its epidemiological history must be taken into account, and whether the infected person has been exposed to a particular environment, for example, the wildlife marketing environment of the seafood market. Once the epidemiological characteristics of the seafood market have been determined, a diagnosis can be made immediately for those who come into contact with the environment, but not all who come out of the seafood market are infected, and vice versa. This raises a question of diagnostic sensitivity. In general, facing a Emerging Infectious Diseases, in order to find and control the source of infection, "better kill a thousand, do not miss a" , is the principle of response. Therefore, it should be emphasized that the sensitivity of the diagnostic method is higher, and the clinical diagnostic criteria may be wider to ensure that no suspicious source of infection is missed.

China News Weekly: When the diagnostic criteria were first established, were there epidemiologists?

Jiang Qingwu: Judging from the result, at that time, things other than etiology were not depicted. After the first group of experts from the public health went to Wuhan on Dec. 31, no epidemiologists or health experts were seen speaking out. The emergence of a new disease, of course, to allow scientists to study, but there are many similar infectious diseases mixed together, to find the cause is very important. However, we also learned from the initial investigation that the epidemiological investigation did not follow up, for example, only saw the south China seafood market, but at that time, some patients did not get the infection from the seafood market. Just looking at a few patients, can not describe the disease behind the real law of transmission, patients from where, where is the source of infection, what is the route of transmission and so on.

Li Liming: In fact, the Emerging Infectious Diseases's response is to do three things: control the source of infection, cut off the route of transmission and protect vulnerable groups. So, a Emerging Infectious Diseases should focus on these three things from the beginning. Disease Control experts are looking for the epidemiology of Emerging Infectious Diseases, to find out its suspicious source of infection, disease incubation period, disease characteristics and disease regularity, in order to take timely preventive and control measures; Clinicians focus on clinical symptoms, signs, diagnostic criteria, treatment, and prognosis to improve the cure rate and reduce mortality; basic research specialists focus on pathogens and their characteristics, the discovery of the full genetic sequencing and structural characteristics of the virus allows the development of diagnostic reagents, vaccines and therapeutic drugs. These three tasks are mutually complementary and can not be dispensed with without one.

But an infectious disease can also be effectively prevented and controlled during an early outbreak or epidemic of Emerging Infectious Diseases, when we don't know what the pathogen is, and this is a concept that we in the public want to build, not necessarily find it, to contain the outbreak. At the same time, it is important to train clinicians in the early diagnosis and clinical differentiation of various Emerging Infectious Diseases, as well as in the prevention of infectious diseases.

China Newsweek: that is to say, even if the cause is unknown, preventive measures can actually be initiated. But the reality in China is that clinicians are more aggressive, so when and how can the epidemiologist intervene?

Li Liming: for example, every hospital emergency department in the United States has experts from the CDC. They are to find new abnormal cases in emergency rooms at any time and establish a highly sensitive infectious disease surveillance system. Disease Control experts work with clinicians, which is called the combination of medicine and prevention. And now we are all, clinical doctors are reporting all kinds of suspicious clinical cases on the front line, and then epidemiologists or disease control experts are going to investigate. This is not synchronized, it is not conducive to the early detection of Emerging Infectious Diseases patients and possible sources of infection.

"The inflection point is not the darkness before dawn, but the equivalent of 12 o'clock at night. "

China Newsweek: Now everyone is talking about inflection point, so the inflection point has really come?

Fung Permadi: First we need to clarify the meaning of the inflection point. The inflection point is actually the day on which the incidence of new cases or the number of new cases is highest, and it should be calculated according to the time of onset, not the reported cases, because the reported cases are all confirmed cases and tend to lag behind, so we see the inflection point, is actually lagging behind the actual situation.

The disease itself has its own laws of development, if not controlled, it is exponential growth. R0, Basic reproduction number, is how many people a person can infect over the course of an infection. If R0 is 2, it's already high, and the trick is to bring that R0 down. So, the inflection point is actually when prevention and control really works, when R0 is less than 1, which is what we define as an epidemiological inflection point.

Hao Yuantao: through some data analysis in the early days, we found that the peak time of new cases was around January 26-29, and then the number of new cases began to decline slowly. This peaks with the number of confirmed cases seen by the public every day, and there happens to be a false peak, because the onset of the disease is not immediately diagnosed, and the time difference coincides with the interval between the onset and the diagnosis.

Jiang Qingwu: from the analysis results found that the peak is now seen after the effect of the city, if we do not take the city, the inflection point may not yet, now may still be another situation. The inflection point is epidemiologically consistent with the lockdown.

Tang Jinling: Why does it coincide with Fengcheng? Because the siege is January 23, the average incubation period is six days, which means that if the siege is effective, the number of new cases should fall after January 29. But you see the Health Commission report, about 5 days later on average, so from the city closed to the beginning of the decline, should be in 10 to 12 days. Sure enough, the public figures began falling on February 5th.

The inflection point we have just mentioned is the peak of onset, that is, January 26-29, but the inflection point is not the darkness before dawn, but is equivalent to 12 o'clock at night, we still have a long way to go. This is one of the most difficult times in the clinic. Because the disease cure time is very long, just like the reservoir, in a lot of water, out of a very slow, resulting in a large number of cumulative cases.

"Many local health officials have no medical background or public health background. "

China News Weekly: For a long time, is the public health sector relatively weak in the right to speak?

Li Liming: usually emergency preparedness, the disease control system every day to do, but did not get enough awareness and attention. Often, when an outbreak comes, the Disease Control Agency and the team are taken seriously, and once the outbreak is gone, the team is not taken seriously, or even marginalized. We often joke that preventive medicine, public health is actually a "self-destructive" team, your prevention work better, the more social and government departments do not pay attention. This has to change!

Hao Yuantao: how to cultivate an excellent public health and Preventive Medicine Team, we are very concerned about, but the current situation is indeed very grim. From the entrance, now the first volunteer to apply for Preventive Medicine Professional Students, even in our excellent public health, the proportion is probably not more than 30% ~ 40% , many are through transfers. I think there are at least two reasons, one is that the state does not pay enough attention to public health institutions, its status is not high; the other is that people do not understand the importance of public health.

In terms of exports, traditionally, many outstanding graduates have gone to work for the CDC, but now outstanding graduates choose not to go to the CDC, but prefer to work in hospitals to do in-hospital infection work and scientific research, or go to some related auxiliary departments, because compared to the hospital, the treatment of disease control is poor, and hospital treatment is much better.

It's all worth thinking about, and finding a way to solve this problem. Otherwise the future building has, the mechanism has been established, but without a good disease control team, or it is difficult to do this thing.

Fung Permadi: Clinical Medicine, oral medicine, all have a point of authorization for a professional doctor's degree, only public health does not have a professional doctor. Several of our schools have applied for many years, but have not been approved. The highest degree in public health is a master's degree. This also reflects the lack of attention to education and administration.

China Newsweek: is the Master of Public Health (MPH) the highest degree in the U. S. education system?

Li Liming: the United States also has a doctor's degree in public health. In addition, all state health directors in the United States are generally MD plus MPH, which is the best educational background for Health Administration. I understand that about a quarter of MD's in medical schools in the United States have MPH degrees, reflecting the importance of public health and its role in the U.S. health care system, public Health is actually a relatively universal vocational education.

Jiang Qingwu: In this epidemic situation, the scene dealt with a lot of cadres. In fact, in many places, the health commission's first and second-in-command do not have a medical background, nor public health education background, which I am very surprised, because this is a strong need for professional knowledge to support the Post. Hubei epidemic early various problems, and this "not professional people are doing professional things" phenomenon has a certain relationship.

Hao Yuantao: the first contact with patients is a clinician, but doctors should not only have the knowledge and skills of individual prevention and control, but also have a higher level of community prevention and control concept. There is a need for post graduate education for doctors, especially in public health, says Continuing education, a professor of medicine at the University of California, San Diego.

China News Week: There is a general discussion, for example, comparing China's Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) with the United States, which has a strong decision-making power. What is the impact of the current system on disease control and Prevention?

Wang Hua: it has something to do with the guiding ideology of Chinese health and the system. It's certainly not as simple as the U.S. CDC. These are two fundamentally different systems. I've been director of the CDC for many years, and I've worked in the civil service for many years, trying to advocate for the CDC, but we can only do what we can within the larger framework of the country.

CDC is a kind of public welfare institutions, its positioning is a technical guidance department. So who, including the director of the National CDC, has the Authority to publish anything about the outbreak? That's not possible.

How to improve the system, the idea is to give it executive power. Like the fire, in the handling of the epidemic, has its own decision-making power, disposal power.

Li Liming: It is impossible to put out a fire in a high-rise building when I drive to that one look, first ask the superior to say what plan we have, wait for the superior to approve us again to put out a fire? !

Wanghua: Now everyone is blaming the CDC. In fact, it has no authority. We joked that it would be better to go back to the old system of epidemic prevention stations, where supervision and monitoring functions were put together. Now that the administrative power is gone, everything depends on how the health administration at the same level makes decisions. It's like when a vaccine goes wrong, it makes no sense to take the director of the CDC off the table.

Ren Jun: The concept of putting prevention first should be upheld for a long time. Just because an epidemic has been dealt with does not mean that we should relax. In fact, since 2003, the state has attached great importance to the construction of disease control systems at all levels. However, after 10 years, slowly on the decline, the concept of prevention-oriented loose again.

Besides, our fine tradition can not be easily given up. For example, after SARS, the former Ministry of Health had a ministerial order No. 40 with a clear plan on how to build the disease control system, but after a period of implementation, it could not be implemented. For example, there used to be a rule that the head of a CDC unit had to be a public health graduate or above. But it doesn't seem to be sticking to that rule anymore.

China News Week: Specifically, what is the direction of Future Disease Control Reform?

Li Liming: We hope that we can refer to the current administration of Traditional Chinese medicine and the State Drug Administration. In the future, the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention should be under the direct administration of the State Council, to further strengthen the role and functions of CDC departments in Handling Public Health Affairs.
